verbs.description: reseed (third-person singular simple present reseeds, present participle reseeding, simple past and past participle reseeded)

entries.meaning: (transitive, intransitive) To sow seeds again; to apply seed to (a plot of land) again.
examples: When the birds ate the seeds he had planted, the farmer was forced to reseed the field.

entries.meaning: Of a non-perennial plant, to produce seeds to ensure the following generation without human intervention; to self-sow.
examples: The marigolds had reseeded themselves in the flower box, so he didn't have to buy new ones this year.

entries.meaning: (computing) To reset the input of an algorithm so as to ensure different results.
examples: The game reseeded its random number algorithm with a time-based value each time the game was restarted.
